The '''libertarian perspective on immigration''' is often regarded as one of the core concepts of [[libertarian]] theory and philosophy.<ref>{{cite book|title=Libertarianism, What Everyone Needs to Know|last=Brennan|first=Jason|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=42, 50, 119, 125|quote= [Libertarians] believe everyone has the right to take employment in any other country, regardless of citizenship. They hold that, except in special circumstances, governments may not forbid citizens from leaving a country, nor may governments forbid foreigners from entering. (Page 42)|via=}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=http://www.libertarianism.org/guides/lectures/immigration-rights|title=Immigration Rights|last=Brennan|first=Jason|date=|website=Libertarianism.org|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-21}}</ref> Some libertarians assert that "[e]fforts by the government to manage the labor market are as apt to fail as similar efforts to protect domestic industries or orchestrate industrial policy. [...] If an immigrant seeks to engage in peaceful, voluntary transactions that do not threaten the freedom or security of the native-born, the government should not interfere".<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Griswold |first= Dan|authorlink=Daniel T. Griswold |editor-first=Ronald |editor-last=Hamowy |editor-link=Ronald Hamowy |encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Libertarianism |title= Immigration|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=yxNgXs3TkJYC |year=2008 |publisher= [[SAGE Publications]], [[Cato Institute]] |location= Thousand Oaks, CA |doi= 10.4135/9781412965811.n145|isbn= 978-1-4129-6580-4 |oclc=750831024| lccn = 2008009151 |pages=235–37, at p. 236 |quote= |ref= }}</ref>

== Libertarian proponents of free immigration ==
{{see also|Free migration}}
[[Samuel Edward Konkin III]] has promoted [[illegal immigration]] as being a key part of the [[Counter-economics|counter-economy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://agorism.info/Counter-Economics.pdf |title=Counter-Economics: what it is, how it works |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325044459/http://agorism.info/Counter-Economics.pdf |archive-date=25 March 2009 |website=agorism.info}}</ref>

Libertarian author [[Jacob Hornberger]], a proponent of freer immigration policies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fff.org/explore-freedom/article/case-unilateral-free-trade-open-immigration/|title=The Case for Unilateral Free Trade and Open Immigration|last=Hornberger|first=Jacob|date=November 1, 1994|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fff.org/explore-freedom/article/lets-stick-traditional-american-values/|title=Let's Stick with Traditional American Values!|last=Hornberger|first=Jacob|date=February 1, 2000|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> argues that [[open border]]s is the only libertarian immigration position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fff.org/2016/05/19/open-borders-libertarian-position-immigration/|title=Open Borders Is the Only Libertarian Immigration Position|last=Hornberger|first=Jacob|date=May 19, 2016|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref>

[[Jeffrey Tucker]], Director of Content at the [[Foundation for Economic Education]],<ref name="FEE">{{cite web|url=http://www.fee.org/authors/detail/jeffrey-a-tucker|title=Jeffrey A. Tucker |publisher=Foundation for Economic Education|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> has been critical of the closed-border arguments made by [[Libertarian conservatism|conservative-leaning libertarians]]:<ref name="fee">{{cite web |url=https://fee.org/articles/why-open-borders/ |title=Why Open Borders? |last=Tucker |first=Jeffrey |authorlink=Jeffrey Tucker |publisher=[[Foundation for Economic Education]] |date=2015-09-14 |accessdate=2016-11-20 }}</ref><ref name="altright">{{cite web |url=https://fee.org/articles/five-differences-between-the-alt-right-and-libertarians/ |title=Five Differences Between the Alt-Right and Libertarianism |last=Tucker |first=Jeffrey |authorlink=Jeffrey Tucker |publisher=[[Foundation for Economic Education]] |date=2016-08-26 |accessdate=2016-11-05 }}</ref> <blockquote>This is a huge debate among people who otherwise swear fealty to "[[limited government]]." Many people who claim to want freedom seem to have no problem with the implications of a closed-border policy: national IDs, national work permits, non-stop surveillance, harassment of all businesses, a "papers please" culture, mass deportation, tens of billions in waste, bureaucrats wrecking the American dream, broken families, [and] the rights of Americans and foreigners transgressed at every turn.<ref name="fee"/></blockquote>

== Libertarian opponents of free immigration ==

A significant strain of [[right-libertarianism|right-libertarian]] thought, associated mainly with [[paleolibertarianism|paleolibertarians]] and [[Hans-Hermann Hoppe|Hoppean]] [[anarcho-capitalism|anarcho-capitalists]], denies [[freedom of movement]] as a [[fundamental rights|fundamental right]], maintaining instead that in their preferred formally stateless society in which all land is privatized fully and absolutely, where economic and political power resides principally with private landowners, a policy of open immigration necessarily amounts to legalized trespassing.

