{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}} {{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Office of the Auditor General | nativename = {{my|ပြည်ထောင်စုစာရင်းစစ်ချုပ်ရုံး}} | nativename_a = | nativename_r = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = {{start date and years ago|df=yes|1972|1|12}} |preceding1 = |agency_type = Agency |jurisdiction = [[Government of Burma]] |headquarters = [[Naypyidaw]] |coordinates = |employees = |budget = | chief1_name = [Maw Than] | chief1_position = Auditor General |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |child3_agency = |child4_agency = |website = {{url|www.oagmac.gov.mm}} }}
The '''Office of the Auditor General''' ({{lang-my|ပြည်ထောင်စုစာရင်းစစ်ချုပ်ရုံး}}; abbreviated '''OAG''') is an independent government body that serves as the [[auditor]] of the [[Government of Burma]]. The Office of the Auditor General is currently held by U Maw Than.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oagmac.gov.mm/content/present}}</ref> The previous Auditor General was U Myo Myint, and his predecessor was U Thein Htaik, appointed by President [[Thein Sein]] on 7 September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:VhIE5-60hPoJ:www.myanmarpresidentoffice.info/en/%3Fq%3Dbriefing-room/orders/2012/09/07/id-641+&cd=3&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us|title=Appointment of Auditor-General of the Union Order No. 34/2012|last=Thein Sein|date=7 September 2012|work=President Office|accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>
==History== The Office of the Auditor General was first formally established during British rule, under the Burma Act of 1935.<ref name="history">{{cite news|url=http://www.oagmac.gov.mm/content/history|title=Profile of Myanmar Supreme Audit Institution |date=2011|work=OFFICE OF THE AUDITOR GENERAL OF THE UNION|accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref> In post-colonial Burma, the Office of the Auditor General was initially established in 1948 under the Parliament's Auditor General Act of 1948, which provided for the appointment of the Auditor General.<ref name="history"/> In 1974, the [[Pyithu Hluttaw]] passed the Council of People’s Inspectors Law, which repealed the 1948 law and merged all auditing agencies, except the Controller of Military Accounts, into a centralised agency, the Central Accounts Office, in January 1974.<ref name="history"/> On 27 September 1988, the [[State Law and Order Restoration Council]] (SLORC), which had recently seized power, appointed an Auditor General and Deputy Auditor General, under Order No. 7/88, and repealed the 1975 Law under Order No. 5/88 and the Auditor General Law of 1988.<ref name="history"/> On 8 March 1994, the [[State Law and Order Restoration Council]] replaced the Accounting Law, which established an Office of the Auditor General of the Union (OAG) that acts as the Secretariat of the [[Myanmar Accountancy Council]], the nation's professional accountancy body.<ref name="oag">{{cite web|url=http://www.oagmac.gov.mm/content/history-0|title=History|work=OFFICE OF THE AUDITOR GENERAL OF THE UNION|accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref> OAG's functions are currently governed by the 2008 [[Constitution of Burma]] and the Auditor General of the Union Law of 2010, which repealed the 1988 law.<ref name="history"/> Thein Htaik died and a new Auditor General, U Myo Myint, was appointed to the position in 2016.
