The '''Tea Party of Nevada''' is a minor [[political party]] in [[Nevada]].<ref name="qualified" /><ref>{{cite web|work=Election Center|title=2010 Filed Candidates|author=[[Nevada Secretary of State]]|publisher=www.nvsos.gov|url=http://nvsos.gov/index.aspx?page=337|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/gop-senate-campaign-chief-downplays-tea-party-impact-in-nevada-86919317.html|title=GOP Senate campaign chief downplays Tea Party impact in Nevada |first=Steve|last=Tetreault|publisher=Las Vegas Review Journal|date=2010-03-08}}</ref> It fielded [[Scott Ashjian]] in the [[United States Senate election in Nevada, 2010]].<ref name="split">J. Patrick Coolican, [http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/mar/05/political-newbie-could-split-gop "Tea Party candidate could siphon GOP votes in bid to remove Harry Reid,"] ''Las Vegas Review-Journal,'' March 5, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/gop-senate-campaign-chief-downplays-tea-party-impact-in-nevada-86919317.html|title=GOP Senate campaign chief downplays Tea Party impact in Nevada |first=Steve|last=Tetreault|publisher=Las Vegas Review Journal|date=2010-03-08}}</ref><ref name="Choice">Kristi Jordan, [http://www.lvrj.com/news/tea-party-hopeful-ashjian-gives-voters-third-choice-86816842.html "Tea Party hopeful Ashjian gives voters third choice,"] ''Las Vegas Review-Journal,'' March 8, 2010.</ref>
==Organization== The Tea Party of Nevada qualified as a minor political party with the Nevada Secretary of State on January 27, 2010.<ref name="qualified">{{cite web|work=Election Center|publisher=www.nvsos.gov|title=Qualified Political Parties|author=[[Nevada Secretary of State]]|url=http://www.nvsos.gov/index.aspx?page=114|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref> Ashjian's supporters created the party by filing more than the 250 signatures needed.<ref name="vogeladmits">{{cite news| last = Vogel | first = Ed | title = Ashjian admits GOP status | work =[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | page =1B | date = April 15, 2010 }}</ref> The Tea Party of Nevada's stated goals include striving to "promote this nation's founding principles of freedom, liberty and a small representative government."<ref name="jourdanquestion">{{cite news| last = Jourdan | first = Kristi |author2=Benjamin Spi | title = Skeptics question Tea Party of Nevada | work = [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | page = 2B | date = February 22, 2010 }}</ref> The party stated in its [[preamble]] that both major political parties were responsible for a "massive national debt" in the United States, and that the "great conservative majority in America" should not believe that the Democrats and Republicans would support their views.<ref name="vogeltea">{{cite news| last = Vogel | first = Ed | title =Tea Party candidate is sued | work = [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | page =1B | date = March 23, 2010 }}</ref>
Ashjian filed his candidacy on March 2, 2010, and became the candidate of the Tea Party of Nevada for [[United States Senate]] in the [[United States Senate election in Nevada, 2010|2010 Nevada general election]].<ref name="stayson" /> Ashjian's candidacy is the only one which appears as the "Tea Party" on the November 2010 ballot.<ref name="notleaving">{{cite news| last = Myers | first = Laura | title = Ashjian not leaving race | work = [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | page = 1B | date = October 1, 2010 }}</ref> In April 2010, Ashjian faced a legal challenge which attempted to remove his name from the ballot.<ref name="remainonballot" /> [[Carson City, Nevada]] district judge James Todd Russell heard arguments on whether Ashjian could remain on the ballot starting on April 14.<ref name="remainonballot" /> Judge Russell ultimately ruled that Ashjian complied with the intent of the law and he could remain on the ballot.<ref name="remainonballot">{{cite news| last = Vogel | first = Ed | title = Tea Party of Nevada candidate Ashjian to remain on ballot | work =[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | publisher = www.lvrj.com | date =April 15, 2010 | url =http://www.lvrj.com/news/tea-party-of-nevada-candidate-ashjian-to-remain-on-ballot-90997149.html | accessdate = 2010-10-13}}</ref> The [[American Independent Party]], which brought the suit against Ashjian,<ref name="remainonballot" /> filed an appeal of the case to the [[Nevada Supreme Court]].<ref name="stayson">{{cite news| last = Dornan | first =Geoff | title =Ashjian stays on the ballot | work = [[Nevada Appeal]]|location=[[Carson City, Nevada]] | date = April 15, 2010 }}</ref><ref name="vogelpartyannounces">{{cite news| last = Vogel | first = Ed | title = Party announces appeal over Ashjian's candidacy | work = [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | page = 2B | date = May 14, 2010 }}</ref> On October 6, 2010, the Nevada Supreme Court issued a unanimous ruling that Ashjian's candidacy would remain on the November 2010 ballot.<ref>{{cite news | title = Nev. Supreme Court: Ashjian 's name stays on ballot | work = [[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|location=[[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] | publisher = [[The New York Times Company]] | date = October 6, 2010 }}</ref><ref name="conservativeslose">{{cite news| last = Vogel | first = Ed |author2=Steve Tetreault | title = Conservatives lose bid to ax Ashjian from Nov. 2 ballot | work = [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | page =6A | date = October 7, 2010 }}</ref>
